===Usage notes===
This term is given as a native Korean equivalent of the Chinese first-person pronouns {{m|zh|我}} and {{m|zh|吾}} in three different Korean-language interpretive ''{{w|gugyeol}}'' glosses to the Buddhist canon, made between the tenth and thirteenth centuries. Interpretive ''gugyeol'' encodes guidelines by which an Korean speaker could have read out a Classical Chinese text in its native Korean translation, much like Japanese {{w|kanbun}}. These three glosses accordingly instruct the Korean reader to pronounce the Chinese first-person pronouns as {{m|oko|又}} or {{m|oko|于}}, allowing us to understand that they are first-person pronouns.

The Middle Korean first-person plural pronoun {{okm-inline|우리|wuli|we; us}} is almost certainly derived from it, although the second syllable remains as of yet inexplicable.

